title: [IOTDB-1415] Fix OOM caused by ChunkCache
body:
## Description
The detailed description could be seen in [JIRA](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/IOTDB-1415)

## Analysis
The details could be found in [Confluence](https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=181307964)

## Solution
Use Caffeine Cache to replace the previous LinkedHashMap.

Caffeine is a high performance Java caching library providing a near optimal hit rate. Caffeine provides an in-memory cache using a Google Guava inspired API. The improvements draw on their experience designing Guava's cache and ConcurrentLinkedHashMap.

The [Tests](https://github.com/ben-manes/caffeine/wiki/Benchmarks) in their website shows that it's much more better than Guava Cache.

In our own [weekly test](http://ise.thss.tsinghua.edu.cn/confluence/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=57212546), Caffeine Cache's performance is same as the previous wrong implementation of master.

title: [IOTDB-1407] Filtering time series based on tags query fails Occasion
body:
https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/IOTDB-1407
5 node , 3 rep.

1. Connect to the client.

2. Run the show timeseries root.turbine where owner=user1 command.
throw :   The key owner is not  a tag.

reason
When the number of nodes is greater than the number of replicas, querying a sequence label is broadcast to all DataGroups. Some DataGroups do not contain the sequence. Therefore, an error is reported when querying the label. As a result, an error is reported for the entire query.

solved
When the root sequence is queried, all DataGroup queries are broadcast.
When a subsequence is queried, the data group of the corresponding subsequence is queried.

title: Hitter compaction strategy
body:
LSM(IoTDB storage) makes full use of disk sequential I/O, can provide high write throughput, and maintains system query performance through the merge mechanism. However, the background merge process consumes a lot of system resources, thus the write performance of the database will greatly degrade under the condition of high system load.

We have collected and analyzed actual queries from some users, found that although there are massive time series in industrial time series data, the query popularity of different time series varies, and hot time series accounts for a low proportion.

Based on the query access characteristics, this pr proposes a query frequency-aware LSM merge mechanism for time series data. The merge mechanism uses hot series merge operations at the low level to meet users timely query requirements; at the high level, full series merge operations are used to garbage-collect redundant data brought by the hot series merge.

body:
This PR fixed the following 2 bugs:
1. For user who does not have CREATE_TIMESERIES privilege, JDBC executeBatch() interface shows execution success, though the unauthorized timeseries are not created.
2. if enabled auto-create schema, CMManager creates SGs for all paths ignoring privilege check. 

Now fixed as:

No permissions for this operation CREATE_TIMESERIES for SQL: "CREATE TIMESERIES root.sg4.d1.s1 WITH DATATYPE=INT64"

title: [IOTDB-1390] Fix unseq compaction loss data bug
body: ## Behavior set compaction_strategy = LEVEL_COMPACTION use the `data` to recover the IoTDB. After Recovery, it will merge the unseq dataautomatically. Afterunseq compaction, the data of some sensor in seq file loss. use the following SQL to check data status before and after unseq compaction. select Channel96 from root.*.J053102.T034.V1 where time >= 2021-05-18 22:32:27 and time <= 2021-05-18 22:32:37; ![9FC2321FEC32B5D6D27ECF043C05AF93](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24886743/119324996-03920080-bcb3-11eb-9d9a-5722b575c7b6.jpg) ## Reason Unseq compaction filter sensor by lexicographic order. However, the input sensor list may be not in lexicographic order. ## Solution Ignore the condition of lexicographic order and use traditional filter means.

Afterunseq compaction, the data of some sensor in seq file loss. use the following SQL to check data status before and after unseq compaction. select Channel96 from root.*.J053102.T034.V1 where time >= 2021-05-18 22:32:27 and time <= 2021-05-18 22:32:37; ![9FC2321FEC32B5D6D27ECF043C05AF93](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24886743/119324996-03920080-bcb3-11eb-9d9a-5722b575c7b6.jpg) ## Reason Unseq compaction filter sensor by lexicographic order. However, the input sensor list may be not in lexicographic order. ## Solution Ignore the condition of lexicographic order and use traditional filter means.

title: [IOTDB-1387] [To rel/0.12] Fix Without Null ALL doesn't take effect in align by device clause
body:
## Description

The details can be seen in JIRA.

## Reasons

Align by device always have one device column which will never be null. While using WITHOUT NULL clause, we shouldn't take device column into consideration.

## Solution

Reset the null state in RowRecord after add the device column. Also decrease the alreadyReturnedRowNum field in QueryDataset while the current RowRecord doesn't satisify the without null constraint.

title: [IOTDB-1022] ANTLR Grammar & Logical Operator for Arithmetic Operations and Nested Operations in SELECT Clauses
body:
**This PR contains two parts of work:**
1. introduce the ANTLR grammer and the logical operator for arithmetic operations and nested operations in SELECT clauses
2. refactor the logical operator / physical plan for select clause (without refactoring, new query features cannot be introduced)


**Change list:**
1. redesign the antlr grammer of `SELECT` clause
2. introduce `ResultColumn` and replace `UDTFContext` by `Expression` to handle arithmetic operations and nested operations
3. refactor `Planner`
4. refactor `LogicalGenerator`
4. refactor `ConcatPathOptimizer` (by introducing `WildcardsRemover`, `ResultColumn` and `Expression`)
5. fix a bug in `RemoveNotOptimizer` (`pathSet` will be set null after optimization)
5. refactor `deduplicate` in `PhysicalGenerator`
5. remove `SFWOperator` and move `SelectOperator`, `FromOperator` and `FilterOperator` into `QueryOperator`. `DeleteDataOperator`, `InsertOperator`, `CreateIndexOperator` and `DropIndexOperator` are refactored due to the change
6. remove `tsAlias` from `PartialPath` and refactor the proccess logic of `as <alias>` clauses. The `tsAlias` related logic is handled in `ResultColumn`
7. introduce `LogicalChecker` to check the correctness of the generated logical operators. This ensures that all checks are processed in the same class.
9. refactor the proccess logic of `rawDataQueryReqToPhysicalPlan` and support it in the cluster mode

**Note:**
The SonarCloud Quality Gate is failed because the new introduced `Expression` is lack of tests (78.3% Coverage < 80%). Related tests will be introduced in further PRs.

title: [IOTDB-1403] Dictionary encoding for TEXT
body: ## Motivation Currently, TEXT is not encoded in IoTDB. While this approach works fine for data with low repetitive patterns, it may result in storage inefficiency and I/O overhead for low-cardinality data, where repetitions happen frequently. To this end, we propose supporting dictionary encoding for TEXT data type, which could provide higher compression rate and faster deserialeraliziation for low-cardinality data. ## Design ## Design choices ### Dictionary building **Choice 1: Character aligned** We scan the page data character by character to build the dictionary incrementally. - [+] The idea has been implemented in LZ encoding and its variants (LZ4, LZW, etc.) - [-] IoTDB already supports LZ4 compression along with other compresion algorithms at compression level, so it may not be necessary to implement it again at encoder level. - [-] Incurs relatively large compression overhead in the dictionary building phase. **Choice 2 (current choice): Datapoint aligned** This method is based on the key assumption that repetition happens frequently at data point level (e.g. in the extreme, all data points have value "Beijing") and does not care about whether repetitions happen across data points. We can then scan the page data point by data point to build the dictionary. Similar idea was implemented in TimeScaleDB ([https://github.com/timescale/timescaledb/blob/eace5ea23b299681a45efa312cf6f51f587d561c/tsl/src/compression/dictionary.h](https://github.com/timescale/timescaledb/blob/eace5ea23b299681a45efa312cf6f51f587d561c/tsl/src/compression/dictionary.h)) - [+] High compression rate when cardinality of data point values are low. - [+] Smaller overhead for compression and decompression compared with choice 1 - [-] Does not capture repetition larger than the length of a data point. ## Encoding format Dictionary encoding supports arbitrary binary data, and works well with data with low cardinality. The encoding format is shown below: ``` := := []... := []... ``` - `map` is an array of strings. During the encoding phase, we can use an in-memory hash table to speed up look-up. - `encodedValues` is an array of indexes corresponding to the indexes of `map`. This allows us to apply (RLE encoding + bit packing) on it during serialisation to further reduce space usage. ## High-level algorithms ### Encoding ```markup func encode(values[]): map[] <- [] encodedValues[] <- [] for value in values: if value in map: encodedValues.push(map.indexOf(value)) else: map.push(value) return [map, encodedValues.push] ``` ### Decoding ```markup func decode(map, encodedValues): values[] <- [] for value in encodedValues: values.push(map[value]) return values ``` ### ~~Adaptive encoding~~ ~~Not all binary data are suitable for dictionary encoding. This, I propose to implemented the ability to dynamically choose whether to use dictionary or plain encoding based on the cardinality of the page (i.e. number of unique values).~~ ## Benchmarks ### Setup Total number of points = 100, 000 Point size = 32B Max page size = 64 * 1024 B ### Results - **Observation 1.** Compression rate (lower the better) increases as the repetitions of values decreases - **Observation 2.** Slowdown (Time taken to for dictionary encoding / time taken for plain encoding) increases as the repetitions of values decreases **Conclusion:** Dictionary encoding works well for data with many repetitions, giving up to 100x smaller space usage with little encoding/decoding overhead. However, it is not suitable for data with few repetitions. title: [To rel/0.12] Filter RowRecord automatically if any column in it is null or all columns are null
body:
## Description
Currently
1. IoTDB will join all the sensor value by its time, and if some sensors don't have values in that timestamp, we will fill it with null. In some analysis scenarios, we only need the row if all the columns of it have value.

2. in group by query, we will fill null for any group by interval if the columns don't have values in that group by interval. However, if all columns in that group by interval are null, maybe users don't need that RowRecord, so we want IoTDB to support this feature.

## Syntax
`select * from root.sg1.d1 WITHOUT NULL ANY` will fix scenario 1 and filter the rows if any column of which is null.
`select last_value(*) from root.testWithoutAllNull.d1 GROUP BY([1, 21), 5ms) WITHOUT NULL ALL` will fix scenario 2 and filter the rows if all columns of which are null.

title: Fix continuous compaction run into dead loop when unseq compaction cannot select candidates
body: Currently, if the unseq compaction cannot select candidates for merge, it will always run again in the same unseq file list in the continuous compaction process. So we have to avoid continuous compaction if the unseq file cannot be selected to be merged.
